Transmembrane signaling between intracellular compartments is often controlled 
by regulated proteolysis. Escherichia coli respond to misfolded or unfolded 
outer-membrane porins (OMPs) in the periplasm by inducing sigma(E)-dependent 
transcription of stress genes in the cytoplasm. This process requires a 
proteolytic cascade initiated by the DegS protease, which destroys a 
transmembrane protein (RseA) that normally binds to and inhibits sigma(E). Here, 
