conserved aspartic acid residues in bacterial signal transduction systems. OmpR 
is a winged helix-turnhelix DNA-binding protein that functions as a global 
regulator in bacteria and is also important in pathogenesis. A detailed 
mechanistic picture of how OmpR binds to DNA and activates transcription is 
lacking. We used NMR spectroscopy to solve the solution structure of the 
C-terminal domain of OmpR (OmpR(C)) and to analyze the chemical shift changes 
