Antibody phage display is a key technology for the generation of recombinant 
(human) antibodies for research, diagnostics and therapy. Most antibody 
fragments can only be folded correctly in the oxidizing environment of the 
periplasm of Escherichia coli. A multitude of leader peptides has been used for 
secretion of antibody::pIII fusion proteins into the periplasm, but a systematic 
study of their impact on the performance of antibody phage display systems has 
not been reported so far. In this work we have analysed the influence of various 
leader peptides on antibody phage display efficiency and production yields of 
soluble antibody fragments. Four leader peptides using the Sec pathway (PelB, 
OmpA, PhoA and pIII) and three using the SRP pathway (DsbA, TorT and TolB) were 
compared. Both pathways are compatible with antibody phage display and the 
production of soluble antibody fragments. The applicability of the SRP pathway 
to antibody phage display and the production of functional scFvs is shown here 
for the first time.

