this resistance pathway. However, for conditions of low pH or intermediate iron 
concentrations, both of which stimulate PmrB/PmrA, we find that PmrD does 
contribute to resistance. We further show that in E. coli, PmrD functions as a 
connector between PhoQ/PhoP and PmrB/PmrA, in contrast with previous reports. In 
this case, activity also depends on PmrB/PmrA stimulation, or on very high 
activation of PhoQ/PhoP. Our results indicate that the importance of the PmrD 
connector in modulating the polymyxin resistance network depends on both the 
network organization and on the environmental conditions associated with PmrB 
stimulation.

