Escherichia coli possesses two well-characterized aconitases (AcnA and AcnB) and 
a minor activity (designated AcnC) that is retained by acnAB double mutants and 
represents no more than 5% of total wild-type aconitase activity. Here it is 
shown that a 2-methylcitrate dehydratase (PrpD) encoded by the prpD gene of the 
propionate catabolic operon (prpRBCDE) is identical to AcnC. Inactivation of 
prpD abolished the residual aconitase activity of an AcnAB-null strain, whereas 
inactivation of ybhJ, an unidentified acnA paralogue, had no significant effect 
on AcnC activity. Purified PrpD catalysed the dehydration of citrate and 
isocitrate but was most active with 2-methylcitrate. PrpD also catalysed the 
dehydration of several other hydroxy acids but failed to hydrate cis-aconitate 
and related substrates containing double bonds, indicating that PrpD is not a 
typical aconitase but a dehydratase. Purified PrpD was shown to be a monomeric 
iron-sulphur protein (M(r) 54000) having one unstable [2Fe-2S] cluster per 
monomer, which is needed for maximum catalytic activity and can be reconstituted 
by treatment with Fe(2+) under reducing conditions.

