Horizontal gene transfer by conjugation plays a major role in bacterial 
evolution, allowing the acquisition of new traits, such as virulence and 
resistance to antibacterial agents. With the increased antibiotic resistance in 
bacterial pathogens, a better understanding of how bacteria modulate conjugation 
under changing environments and the genetic factors involved is needed. Despite 
the evolutionary advantages conjugation may confer, the process can be quite 
stressful for the donor cell. Here, we characterize the ability of TraR, encoded 
