The frequency of illegitimate recombination has been measured by a lambda bio 
transducing phage assay during the induction of the E. coli lambda cI857 
lysogen. Illegitimate recombination falls into two classes, short 
homology-independent and short homology-dependent illegitimate recombination. 
The former involves sequences with virtually no homology, and is mediated by DNA 
topoisomerases and controlled by the DNA binding protein HU. The latter is 
induced by UV irradiation or other DNA damaging agents and requires short 
regions of homology, usually contain 4 to 13 base pairs, at sites involved in 
recombination. It has been shown that the RecJ exonuclease promotes short 
homology-dependent illegitimate recombination, but that the RecQ helicase 
suppresses it. In addition, we have shown that the overexpression of RecE and 
RecT enhances the frequencies of spontaneous and UV-induced illegitimate 
recombination and that the RecJ, RecF, RecO, and RecR functions are required for 
this RecE-mediated illegitimate recombination. Moreover, we have also indicated 
that RecQ plays a role in the suppression of RecE-mediated illegitimate 
recombination, with the participation of DnaB, Fis, ExoI, and H-NS. Models have 
been proposed for these modes of recombination: the DNA gyrase subunit exchange 
model for short homology-independent illegitimate recombination and the 
"double-strand break and join" model for short homology-dependent illegitimate 
recombination. Many features of these models remain to be tested in future 
studies.

